org.jscsi.target.scsi.cdb

Class CommandDescriptorBlock

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.jscsi.target.scsi.cdb.CommandDescriptorBlock
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    FormatUnitCDB, InquiryCDB, ModeSense6Cdb, ReadCapacityCdb, ReadOrWriteCdb, ReportLunsCDB, RequestSenseCdb, SendDiagnosticCdb, TestUnitReadyCdb

    public abstract class CommandDescriptorBlock
extends Object
    An abstract class for accessing the variables common to Command Descriptor Blocks of all sizes.

    A Command Descriptor Blocks is a blocks of multiple bytes that contains a ScsiOperationCode, specifying a command the SCSI initiator wants the SCSI target to perform and related fields, which determine details of the ordered task.

    Since all fields in the Control byte except for the Normal ACA bit are either reserved, obsolete, or vendor specific, the NACA bit can be accessed directly from this class.

    Author:
    Andreas Ergenzinger

    • Constructor Detail

      • CommandDescriptorBlock

        public CommandDescriptorBlock(ByteBuffer buffer)
        The abstract constructor.

        Deserializes the first byte containing the SCSI Operation Code and the Control byte.

        The passed ByteBuffer parameter must have a capacity ≥ the length of the specific command descriptor block. Since this is assured by the SCSICommandParser.getCDB() method, which always returns ByteBuffer objects with capacity 16, no checks will be performed.

        Parameters:
        buffer - contains the serialized CDB starting at index position zero

      • isNormalACA

        public final boolean isNormalACA()
        The NACA (Normal ACA) bit specifies whether an auto contingent allegiance (ACA) is established if the command terminates with CHECK CONDITION status. A NACA bit set to one specifies that an ACA shall be established. A NACA bit set to zero specifies that an ACA shall not be established.
        Returns:
        true if the Normal ACA bit in the CDB's Control byte is set and false if it is not.

        public final FieldPointerSenseKeySpecificData[] getIllegalFieldPointers()
        Returns null if there were no illegal fields in the serialized CDB passed to the constructor, or an array of appropriate FieldPointerSenseKeySpecificData, that have to be enclosed in the SenseData returned to the initiator (with sense key SenseKey.ILLEGAL_REQUEST and additional sense code and sense code qualifier AdditionalSenseCodeAndQualifier.INVALID_FIELD_IN_CDB).
        Returns:
